              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>No regulations at all.</strong> No license, no night limit, no MAT, investment properties allowed.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col highlight-green"><strong>Ajax</strong></div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>No regulations.</strong> Permitted without specific STR bylaws.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col highlight-green"><strong>Pickering</strong></div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight"><strong>No regulations.</strong> Permitted without specific STR bylaws.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col"><strong>Vaughan</strong></div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Regulated. Principal residence required, license needed, 4% MAT.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col"><strong>Toronto (Scarborough)</strong></div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Regulated. Principal residence, 180 nights/year, registration, 8.5% MAT.</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p><strong>Richmond Hill</strong> is the standout. It shares a border with Markham, has comparable property values, and currently has zero STR-specific regulations. No license, no principal residence requirement, no night limit, and no MAT. If you're looking to buy an investment property for Airbnb in the York Region area, Richmond Hill is worth a serious look. Read our <a href="/blog/richmond-hill-airbnb-short-term-rental-rules-2026">complete Richmond Hill guide</a> for the full breakdown.</p>

          <p><strong>Ajax and Pickering</strong> in Durham Region are also unregulated. They're further east but offer lower entry prices than central York Region. If you're an investor, these markets give you more flexibility without the regulatory overhead.</p>

          <p>Thinking of <a href="https://www.airbnb.ca/rp/jeffp3498?p=stay&s=67" target="_blank" rel="noopener">getting started on Airbnb</a> in one of these cities? Sign up through our link and get a free consultation on setting up your listing.</p>
          <p class="fine-print">*This article contains a referral link. We may earn a small commission at no cost to you.</p>

          <h2 id="corporate-housing">Corporate Housing Demand in Markham</h2>
          <p>Markham is one of the GTA's strongest markets for corporate housing, and that's directly relevant if you're pivoting to mid-term rentals. Here's why the demand is so consistent:</p>

          <h3>The Tech Corridor</h3>
          <p>Markham is sometimes called "Canada's High-Tech Capital" (the city literally trademarked that phrase). The numbers back it up:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>IBM Canada</strong> headquarters on Warden Avenue employs thousands</li>
            <li><strong>AMD, Qualcomm, Huawei, and Lenovo</strong> all have significant Markham offices</li>
            <li><strong>Over 1,500 tech companies</strong> operate in the city</li>
            <li><strong>Markham Centre</strong> is being developed as a major mixed-use tech and residential hub</li>
          </ul>

          <p>When these companies bring in consultants, project managers, or new hires from out of town (or out of country), those people need furnished housing for weeks or months. A well-furnished 2 bedroom condo near Highway 7 and Warden is gold for this tenant pool.</p>

          <h3>The Cultural Connection</h3>
          <p>Markham has one of the most diverse populations in Canada. Over 78% of residents identify as visible minorities, with large Chinese, South Asian, and Filipino communities. This creates unique mid-term demand:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Families visiting from overseas</strong> for extended stays (1 to 3 months)</li>
            <li><strong>Parents coming to help with newborns</strong> who need their own space nearby</li>
            <li><strong>Students at nearby universities</strong> (York University, University of Toronto Scarborough) whose families want a Markham base</li>
            <li><strong>Business owners from Asia</strong> exploring Canadian expansion, often staying 1 to 6 months</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Key Neighbourhoods for Mid-Term Demand</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Markham Centre (Highway 7 and Warden):</strong> Highest condo density, closest to tech offices. Best for corporate tenants.</li>
            <li><strong>Unionville:</strong> Charming Main Street, restaurants, and walkability. Great for families and longer stays.</li>
            <li><strong>Cornell:</strong> Newer community with modern homes. Popular with relocating families.</li>
            <li><strong>Markham Village:</strong> Established area near downtown Markham. Good mix of townhomes and condos.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 id="tax-obligations">Tax Obligations for Mid-Term Rentals</h2>
          <p>Even though mid-term rentals aren't subject to Markham's STR ban, you still have tax obligations:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
            <div class="comparison-header">
              <div class="comparison-col">Tax</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Mid-Term Rental (30+ days)</div>
            </div>
